Using time series of daily or deaths cases, unlike cumulative series, it is possible to estimate their smoothed curves. These curves approximate their growth rate functions, which allow us to identify their inflection points. In this case, we set k = 50 to increase the degree of smoothness, using \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\varsigma _{t} \thicksim Pois(\lambda)$\end{document}ςt∽Pois(λ) i.i.d. random variables. Recall: the lower the k values, the smoother the fitted curve is, which helps to find the most relevant inflection points, the local maxima. Otherwise, the fitted curve would be very wiggly, making all the points local minima and maxima.

When using Eqs. (2–3), we assumed that the residuals follow a normal distribution, with a constant variance: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
